Welcome!
On the following pages you will be able to participate in the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test.

This implementation of the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test was designed and programmed by Julian Discher, Robert Mierzwa, and Sergej Schmidt as an assignment for a seminar by Dr. Yury Shevchenko at the University of Konstanz using lab.js. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.

Instructions

In this task, you need to match a card presented at the bottom of the screen to one of the four cards presented at the top of the screen.

Click on one of the four cards that matches the card at the bottom. You will then get feedback on whether or not your choice was correct.

This implementation of the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test was designed and programmed by Julian Discher, Robert Mierzwa, and Sergej Schmidt as an assignment for a seminar by Dr. Yury Shevchenko at the University of Konstanz using lab.js. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.

Instructions

For example: If you were matching by color, you would click on the first card. If you were matching by shape, you would click on the fourth card. If you were matching by number, you would click on the third card.


This implementation of the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test was designed and programmed by Julian Discher, Robert Mierzwa, and Sergej Schmidt as an assignment for a seminar by Dr. Yury Shevchenko at the University of Konstanz using lab.js. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.

Instructions
Furthermore, you only have four seconds to respond! So please try to respond quickly.

You will now have time to practice. Try to figure out whether you have to match the following five cards by color, number, or shape.

This implementation of the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test was designed and programmed by Julian Discher, Robert Mierzwa, and Sergej Schmidt as an assignment for a seminar by Dr. Yury Shevchenko at the University of Konstanz using lab.js. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.

Instructions

If you did not figure this out in time, don't worry: This is what the practice trials were for. Now that you have an idea what the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test looks like you are prepared to continue with the main task! This will take six minutes. Please make sure that you are not going to be distracted during this time.

This implementation of the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test was designed and programmed by Julian Discher, Robert Mierzwa, and Sergej Schmidt as an assignment for a seminar by Dr. Yury Shevchenko at the University of Konstanz using lab.js. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.

this.data.n_trials = 0; // number of trials
this.data.n_correct = 0; // number of correct responses
this.data.n_timeout = 0; // number of "too slow" messages: the participant did not react in time
this.data.n_errors = 0; // total number of errors i.e. wrong responses ("too slow" is not included)
this.data.n_perservation = 0; // number of perservation errors
this.data.n_non_perservation = 0; // number of non-perservation errors

Your Performance

The test is now over. The following table shows your performance. If you want you can now take the time to note it down. What these values mean and how they can be indicative of mental illness and brain damage is explained on the upcoming page.

Trials ${this.state.n_trials} ${100 * this.state.n_trials / this.state.n_trials}%
Correct ${this.state.n_correct} ${100 * this.state.n_correct / this.state.n_trials}%
Too slow ${this.state.n_timeout} ${100 * this.state.n_timeout / this.state.n_trials}%
Total errors ${this.state.n_errors} ${100 * this.state.n_errors / this.state.n_trials}%
Perservation errors ${this.state.n_perservation} ${100 * this.state.n_perservation / this.state.n_trials}%
Non-perservation errors ${this.state.n_non_perservation} ${100 * this.state.n_non_perservation / this.state.n_trials}%
This implementation of the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test was designed and programmed by Julian Discher, Robert Mierzwa, and Sergej Schmidt as an assignment for a seminar by Dr. Yury Shevchenko at the University of Konstanz using lab.js. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.

Mental Illness and Brain Damage

Healthy individuals make very few unnecessary mistakes in this task (total errors < 25%). However, patients with difficulties in executive functions (e.g. planning, strategy formation) make a lot of perservation errors (perservation errors > 25%) because they fail to adapt to changes of the matching rule and come up with a new strategy (perservation = sticking to the old strategy). As the frontal lobe is associated with executive functions patients with impaired frontal lobe functioning (e.g. patients with schizophrenia) make more perservation errors than healthy individuals. On the other hand, patients whose perception or attention is impaired make more non-perservation errors than healthy control.

This way the Wisconsin Card Sorting Test can help indicate where patients have deficits: Do they have problems recognizing the strategy or do they simply don't recognize the cards themselves? The number of perservation and non-perservation errors gives a hint at the answer to this question. Of course, a meaningful diagnosis involves much more steps than such a small test can provide but now you have an idea what a neuropsychological test can look like.

We hope that you were able to enjoy our implementation of the Wisonsin Card Sorting Test. Please feel free to contact robert.mierzwa@uni-konstanz.de if you have any questions or suggestions for improvement.
